To make the bot only throw excess cooked pork chops, we need to modify the `throwItems()` function to only include pork chops in the `itemsToThrow` array if the bot has more than one. We can do this by adding an additional check to the filter function:

async function throwItems() {
  const porkchopId = bot.registry.itemsByName.cooked_porkchop.id;
  const porkChops = bot.inventory.items().filter(item => item.type === porkchopId);

  const excessPorkChops = porkChops.length > 1 ? porkChops.length - 1 : 0;

  const itemsToThrow = bot.inventory.items().filter(item => {
    if (!item.name.toLowerCase().includes('leather') && item.type !== porkchopId) {
      return true;
    }
    if (item.type === porkchopId && excessPorkChops > 0) {
      excessPorkChops--;
      return true;
    }
    return false;
  });

  const goal = new GoalNear(5114880, 134, 5096970, 2);
  await bot.pathfinder.goto(goal);
  for (const item of itemsToThrow) {
    await bot.tossStack(item);
  }
  dig1();
}

In this modified code, we first count the total number of cooked pork chops in the bot's inventory and calculate how many we need to keep (in this case, 1). We then modify the filter function to include pork chops in the `itemsToThrow` array only if the bot has excess pork chops to throw (i.e. the bot has more than one) and to throw only one excess pork chop at a time. This ensures that the bot will only throw excess cooked pork chops and keep at least one in its inventory.

