Here's an example implementation of the `splitData` function that can work with the `II` and `m` variables of size 100820x72:

```
function [trainData, testData, trainLabels, testLabels] = splitData(data, labels, testRatio)
    % data: N x D matrix of N samples with D dimensions
    % labels: N x 1 vector of class labels for each sample
    % testRatio: ratio of samples to use for testing (e.g. 0.3 for 30%)

    uniqueLabels = unique(labels);
    numLabels = length(uniqueLabels);
    trainData = [];
    testData = [];
    trainLabels = [];
    testLabels = [];

    for i = 1:numLabels
        labelIndices = find(labels == uniqueLabels(i));
        numLabelSamples = length(labelIndices);
        numTestSamples = round(numLabelSamples * testRatio);
        numTrainSamples = numLabelSamples - numTestSamples;
        permutedIndices = randperm(numLabelSamples);
        testIndices = labelIndices(permutedIndices(1:numTestSamples));
        trainIndices = labelIndices(permutedIndices(numTestSamples+1:end));
        testData = [testData; data(testIndices,:)];
        trainData = [trainData; data(trainIndices,:)];
        testLabels = [testLabels; labels(testIndices,:)];
        trainLabels = [trainLabels; labels(trainIndices,:)];
    end
end
```

In this implementation, we take in the `data` matrix of size N x D and the `labels` vector of size N x 1. We also take in a `testRatio` parameter (e.g., 0.3 for 30%) that determines the proportion of samples to use for testing. 

We first determine the unique labels in the dataset and the number of labels (i.e., classes). We then loop over each label and split the data into training and testing sets for that label. For each label, we randomly permute the indices of the samples and select a portion of them for testing (based on the specified test ratio). The rest of the samples are used for training. We concatenate the training and testing sets across all labels and return them as outputs. 

To use this function with the `II` and `m` variables, you could call it as follows:

```
[trainData, testData, trainLabels, testLabels] = splitData(II, m', 0.3);
```

Note that we transpose the `m` variable to make it a column vector and pass it as labels to the function. Also, we use a test ratio of 0.3, which means we will use 30% of the samples for testing and the remaining 70% for training. You can adjust this ratio as needed for your application.

